\section{Introduction}

Reinsurance contracts play an important role in the insurance sector, which provide protection to the insurer’s 
financial statements when the risk is too high and you want to minimize the possibility of loss, due to the transfer 
the risk to different insurance companies (mainly to socalled reinsurance company) through this type of contracts.


Through the reinsurance contract, insurance and reinsurance companies agree to give in and accept part or 
all of one or more risks, agreeing premiums insurance policy and payments of claims covered by the policy. 
In these contracts may be several types and variants of reinsurance contracts, since they depend on agreements 
on the distribution of risk taken. Unfortunately, the means on how to choose the types of reinsurance and their 
parameters often solely rely on business experience or simple rules of thumb (Oesterreicher). 
These processes need to have more rigorous treatments due to the importance of the decision making role.

This document presents the multi objective evolutionary algorithm (MOEA), which is a method inspired in 
the natural selection phenomenon and that include a population of competing solutions, which applied in 
the insurance area minimize the expenses that come with contracting reinsurance protections and at the same 
time to minimize the retained risk after reinsurance (Oesterreicher).

(Following paragraph: brief explanation of the method, in construction)

By using a multi-objective evolutionary algorithm (MOEA) we obtain a Pareto-optimal set (a two dimensional curve) 
of solutions. In addition to that the evolutionary approach gives us the flexibility to change the modeling 
(e.g. the premium principle), to extend the objective functions (into yet unsolved combinations) and to add 
true constraints (like capital requirements) without having problems with non-convexity or non-differentiability.

